\title{Sparsity by Worst-Case Quadratic Penalties}
\description{
Fits the solution paths of classical sparse regression models with efficient
active set algorithms by solving small sub-problems. Depending on the penalty,
the sub-problems can be  solved exactly (\emph{i.e.} for the LASSO) or with generic
solvers. The available optimizer includes quadratic solvers, Newton-based
approaches and generic FISTA or PGD algorithms. Also provides a few methods for
model selection purpose (information criteria, cross-validation, stability selection).
}
\details{
\strong{Quadrupen} covers the following regularizers
\itemize{
\item LASSO (Least Absolute Shrinkage and Selection Operator)
\item SCAD (Smoothly Clip Absolute Deviation)
\item MCP (Minimax Concave Penalty)
\item Group-LASSO (L1/L2 or L1/Linfty)
\item Cooperative-LASSO
\item Sparse Group-LASSO and Sparse Cooperative-LASSO
\item Bounded Regression (L-infty norm).
}

For all these regularizers, \strong{Quadrupen} offers the possibility to add an
ridge-like "structured" penalty to embed some external knowledge about
the statistical dependence between the features. This is sometimes referred to as the
"Structured Elastic-Net".

We also provide in the package the implementation of the Generalized Fused-LASSO originally
proposed by Holger Hoefling now archived from CRAN (\href{https://github.com/cran/FusedLasso}{original repo here}).

While likely not as fast as highly specialized packages like \emph{glmnet},
the use of a working set algorithm combined with efficient solvers, sparse matrix support when applicable, and templated C++ code makes it both competitive and versatile.
\subsection{Features:}{

The more important functions of the package are \code{\link[=sparse_lm]{sparse_lm()}} and \code{\link[=group_sparse_lm]{group_sparse_lm()}} functions,
which fits a linear model either with element-wise or group-wise sparsity. The functions
\code{\link[=lasso]{lasso()}}, \code{\link[=elastic_net]{elastic_net()}}, \code{\link[=scad]{scad()}}, \code{\link[=mcp]{mcp()}} and \code{\link[=group_lasso]{group_lasso()}}, \code{\link[=group_l1linf]{group_l1linf()}}, \code{\link[=coop_lasso]{coop_lasso()}},
\code{\link[=sparse_group_lasso]{sparse_group_lasso()}}, \code{\link[=sparse_coop_lasso]{sparse_coop_lasso()}} are only aliases for these two main functions.

The functions \code{\link[=lava]{lava()}}, \code{\link[=group_lava]{group_lava()}}, \code{\link[=fused_lasso]{fused_lasso()}} and \code{\link[=bounded_reg]{bounded_reg()}} are also available and specific.

We also included R6 and S3 methods for plotting, cross-validation and for the stability
selection procedure of Meinshausen and Buhlmann (2010).
